1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,229
Lesson 6: Emergence.

2
00:00:03,229 --> 00:00:07,723
In this lesson, we'll define 'emergence'
and explain why emergent outcomes are

3
00:00:07,723 --> 00:00:09,591
difficult to predict in advance.

4
00:00:10,591 --> 00:00:14,499
Emergence refers to behaviours or
outcomes that arise from the interactions

5
00:00:14,499 --> 00:00:18,670
between the different parts of a system.
The system produces something that none

6
00:00:18,670 --> 00:00:20,994
of its components could produce in
isolation.

7
00:00:20,994 --> 00:00:25,704
Take "team culture". The individual
members of a team do relatively discrete

8
00:00:25,704 --> 00:00:30,727
things: they communicate in certain ways,
they respond to requests within certain

9
00:00:30,727 --> 00:00:34,369
timeframes, they handle conflict using
particular patterns.

10
00:00:34,369 --> 00:00:37,202
None of them individually creates a
culture.

11
00:00:37,202 --> 00:00:41,989
Yet from the accumulation of those
interactions over time, something arises

12
00:00:41,989 --> 00:00:47,034
which we recognise as a team's character.
That character is emergent; no single

13
00:00:47,034 --> 00:00:49,880
person designed it and no policy mandated
it.

14
00:00:49,880 --> 00:00:53,224
The same dynamic operates at an
organisational level.

15
00:00:53,224 --> 00:00:57,585
When a firm develops a reputation for
being the most responsive in its market,

16
00:00:57,585 --> 00:01:00,190
it didn't come from any one person's
behaviour.

17
00:01:00,190 --> 00:01:04,765
It emerged from a pattern of interactions
across the organisation over time,

18
00:01:04,765 --> 00:01:09,524
reinforced by structures, incentives, and
norms that nobody sat down to design.

19
00:01:09,524 --> 00:01:14,798
So, if we understand emergence, why does
it consistently surprise us? The answer

20
00:01:14,798 --> 00:01:19,471
lies in how we tend to explain outcomes;
we explain them by pointing to

21
00:01:19,471 --> 00:01:20,205
components.

22
00:01:20,205 --> 00:01:24,880
When something goes well, we look for the
person who made it happen. When something

23
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:27,217
goes wrong, we look for whoever caused
it.

24
00:01:27,217 --> 00:01:31,633
However, in complex systems, many of the
most significant outcomes aren't

25
00:01:31,633 --> 00:01:36,477
traceable to any individual component;
they emerge from the interactions between

26
00:01:36,477 --> 00:01:36,784
them.

27
00:01:38,784 --> 00:01:42,777
When we understand that emergence can't
be traced to a single cause, we can

28
00:01:42,777 --> 00:01:44,450
respond to it more effectively.

29
00:01:44,450 --> 00:01:49,511
The shift systems thinking asks us to
make, when we encounter surprising or

30
00:01:49,511 --> 00:01:54,435
undesirable outcomes, is from "who caused
this?" to "what produced this?"

31
00:01:55,435 --> 00:01:59,893
The shift is toward understanding the
structural conditions that made the

32
00:01:59,893 --> 00:02:04,413
outcome more likely. Asking "who caused
this" almost always leads us to an

33
00:02:04,413 --> 00:02:05,094
individual.

34
00:02:05,094 --> 00:02:09,524
That individual may well have contributed
to the outcome, but if we stop there,

35
00:02:09,524 --> 00:02:13,500
we've addressed a symptom and left the
structural conditions unchanged.

36
00:02:13,500 --> 00:02:18,882
The next person in that role will face
the same conditions and produce a similar

37
00:02:18,882 --> 00:02:24,196
result. Asking "what produced this" leads
us to the interactions, the incentive

38
00:02:24,196 --> 00:02:28,965
structures, the feedback loops, and the
delays that shaped the outcome.

39
00:02:28,965 --> 00:02:34,071
Those are the things that, if addressed,
will change what the system produces.

40
00:02:34,071 --> 00:02:39,441
This shift applies across team dynamics,
organisational strategy, and professional

41
00:02:39,441 --> 00:02:40,900
practice of all kinds.

42
00:02:42,900 --> 00:02:44,711
Let's stop the lesson here.

43
00:02:44,711 --> 00:02:48,792
In this lesson, we first defined
emergence as behaviour that arises from

44
00:02:48,792 --> 00:02:51,723
interactions rather than from individual
components.

45
00:02:51,723 --> 00:02:55,903
We then examined why emergence surprises
us.

46
00:02:55,903 --> 00:03:00,368
Finally, we introduced the shift from
individual blame to structural analysis

47
00:03:00,368 --> 00:03:02,776
as a core discipline of systems thinking.

